Call for Papers : AIMLAI Workshop (Advances in Interpretable Machine Learni=
ng and Artificial Intelligence)=20

Metz, 22 janvier 2019=20

An event co-located with 19th EGC conference.=20

[ https://project.inria.fr/aimlai/ | https://project.inria.fr/aimlai/  ]=20








***************************************************=20
Important dates=20


    * Submission deadline: 03/12/2018=20
    * Notification to authors: 18/12/2018=20
    * Camera-ready deadline: 08/01/2019=20



*************************************************** About AIMLAI=20


Recent technological advances rely on accurate decision support systems tha=
t have been constructed as black boxes. That is, the system=E2=80=99s inter=
nal logic is not available to the user, either for financial reasons or due=
 to the complexity of system. This lack of explanation can lead to technica=
l, ethical, and legal issues. For example, if the control module of a self-=
driving car failed at detecting a pedestrian, it becomes crucial to know wh=
y the system erred. In some other cases, the decision system may reflect un=
acceptable biases that can generate distrust. Recently, the European Parlia=
ment adopted the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), a law that for =
the first time in history stipulates the right for all individuals to obtai=
n comprehensible explanations of the logic involved when automated decision=
 making takes place. For all these reasons, multiple research approaches pr=
ovide comprehensible explanations for traditionally accurate but black-box-=
like machine learning algorithms such as neural networks or random forests.=
 AIMLAI aims at gathering researchers, experts and professionals interested=
 in the topic of interpretable ML and interpretable AI.=20

The AIMLAI workshop is co-located with the conference [ https://egc2019.sci=
encesconf.org/ | EGC ] (Extraction et Gestion des Connaissances), which wil=
l take place in Metz (France) from the 21st to 25th of January 2019 . AIMLA=
I envisions to become a discussion venue for the advent of novel interpreta=
ble algorithms and explainability modules that mediate the communication be=
tween complex ML/AI systems and users. Research Topics=20


    * Interpretable classifiers and regressors=20
    * Generating explanations for ML and AI algorithms=20
    * AI Ethics=20
    * Explainable Recommendation Models=20

Submission instructions=20


We invite the submission of both in-progress and completed works. The works=
hop welcomes fully academic as well as application papers. Submissions must=
 have up to 4 pages and must comply with the RNTI (Revue des Nouvelles Tech=
nologie de l=E2=80=99Information) proceedings format. The manuscript Latex =
template for workshop proceedings is available here: [ http://www.editions-=
rnti.fr/files/RNTI-X-Y2.1.zip | http://www.editions-rnti.fr/files/RNTI-X-Y2=
.1.zip ] . Papers should be submitted in PDF format using the [ https://eas=
ychair.org/conferences/?conf=3Daimlai19 | online easychair submission syste=
m ] .=20

After the review process (two reviewers per paper), accepted work will be a=
llocated time for oral presentation and discussion during the workshop. At =
least one author of each accepted paper must be registered to the workshop.=
 The official language of the workshop will be French, however we accept su=
bmissions in English from non-French speakers.=20




